# n8n Workflow Build Rules

## Structure
- One workflow = one business outcome. If it does two things, split it.
- Build in this order: Trigger → Validate → Transform → Logic → Output
- Every webhook workflow must have a structured error response path

## Naming
- Workflow names: `kebab-case`, verb-noun (e.g., `lead-intake`, `invoice-send`)
- Node names: Title Case, action-focused (e.g., `Validate Fields`, `Return Error`)
- Exported filename must match the workflow name exactly: `lead-intake.json`

## Credentials
- Never put API keys, tokens, or secrets in workflow JSON or payloads
- All credentials go in the n8n Credentials UI only
- Check `credentials-checklist.md` in the client folder before building

## Error Handling
- Add error branches on all nodes that call external services
- Return this shape from webhook errors:
  ```json
  { "success": false, "error": "<slug>", "fields": [], "received_at": "<iso>" }
  ```

## Code Nodes
- Use built-in nodes first. Only use Code nodes when there is no alternative.
- Keep Code nodes under 30 lines. Name them clearly.

## Testing
- Every workflow needs at least two test payloads: happy-path and one error case
- Test payloads live in `clients/<name>/payloads/`
- Run both before exporting

## Export and Commit
- Export workflow JSON after every meaningful change
- Save to `clients/<name>/workflows/<workflow-name>.json`
- Commit with: `feat(<client>): <what changed>`

## Output Metadata
- Include `workflow_version`, `received_at`, and `lead_status` (or equivalent) in all webhook responses
